    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, our offensive core is anchored by **Jackson Merrill** (65.98) and **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (63.81). **Jackson Merrill** draws a favorable profile against Castillo, benefiting from a 13% platoon efficiency boost that elevates his raw projection to elite territory. Similarly, **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** remains an auto-start despite facing Sproat; his sustained elite xwOBA of .384 serves as the primary floor-raiser, ensuring he remains in the UTIL slot even against a competent right-handed arm. **Luis Garc\u00eda Jr.** (60.68) also clears our \"Strong\" start threshold; he is poised to exploit a significant platoon advantage against Ashcraft, making him our most efficient internal option at 2B for this rotation.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today's depth chart involved **Jacob Wilson** (59.72), who narrowly edged out the bench. While his score is bolstered by a 10% park factor and 10% SP skill advantage, his BvP history remains a slight negative, causing some friction in the model. He ultimately gets the nod over **Nolan Schanuel** (47.95), who was the strongest candidate on our bench. **Nolan Schanuel** fell short primarily due to the difficulty of his matchup against Fried and the superior situational alignment for our active infielders. Meanwhile, **Gunnar Henderson** (48.62) carries the highest risk of the starters today; his score is suppressed significantly by a 15% platoon penalty against Messick, reminding us that even our stars must be managed strictly against difficult left-handed matchups to maximize overall efficiency.\n\nOwners should keep a close eye on **Gunnar Henderson** and **Josh Jung** (54.90) as they face tough left-handed starters; while their talent is indisputable, their output in 5x5 Roto is susceptible to downward variance when the platoon split is unfavorable. We continue to prioritize stolen base potential and efficient batting average, which is why players like **Nasim Nunez** remain on the bench\u2014his speed is elite, but the unfavorable 9th-order slot and the specific threat posed by Ashcraft in terms of holding runners (62% SB efficiency) dictated his exclusion today. We are playing for long-term category density, and today\u2019s lineup reflects a calculated attempt to balance raw power with situational platoon alignment.",
